TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
This is like the preceding problem.
Let the polynomial \(p\) be defined by
\[p(x) = x^3-2x^2+3x+4.\]
Then \(p(2x+1)=\) \{ ans_rule(3) \}\(x^3\)
EOT
&ANS(num_cmp(8));
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
\(+\) \{ ans_rule(3) \} \(x^2\)
EOT
&ANS(num_cmp(4));
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
\(+\) \{ ans_rule(3) \} \(x\)
EOT
&ANS(num_cmp(4));
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
\(+\) \{ ans_rule(3) \},
EOT
&ANS(num_cmp(6));



TEXT(EV3(<<'EOT'));
$BR Hint: 
The notation \(p(2x+1)\) means "replace \(x\) with \(2x+1\) in the
definition of \(p\).
EOT

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));
$BR $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD
We obtain 
\[
\begin{array}{rcl}
p(2x+1) &=& (2x+1)^3-2(2x+1)^2+3(2x+1)+4 \\
       &=& (8x^3+12x^2+6x+1) -2(4x^2+4x+1) +6x+3+4 \\
       &=& 8x^3+4x^2+4x+6.\\
\end{array}
\]

EOT


